{"title_page": "Trevor Platt", "text_new": "{{short description|British marine scientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Trevor Platt\n| honorific_suffix  = FRS, FRSC\n| image = Trevor_Platt.jpg\n| birth_date        = August 12, 1942\n| birth_place       = Salford, UK\n| death_date        = April 6, 2020\n| death_place       = Plymouth, UK\n| fields            = Oceanography\n| workplaces        = Bedford Institute of Oceanography, Plymouth Marine Laboratory\n| alma_mater        = Dalhousie University\n| known_for         = [https://doi.org/10.4319/lo.1976.21.4.0540 Mathematical formulation of the relationship between photosynthesis and light for phytoplankton] ([[PI curve|P-I curve]])\n| awards            = G. Evelyn Hutchinson Award, A.G. Huntsman Award\n| spouse = Shubha Sathyendranath\n}}\n\n'''Trevor Charles Platt''', FRS, FRSC (August 12, 1942 - April 6, 2020) was a British and Canadian biological oceanographer who was distinguished for his fundamental contributions to quantifying primary production by phytoplankton at various scales of space and time in the ocean.<ref name=\"PML2020\">{{cite web |last1=Anonymous |title=In memoriam: Professor Trevor Platt FRS |url=https://www.pml.ac.uk/News_and_media/News/In_memoriam_Professor_Trevor_Platt_FRS |website=Plymouth Marine Laboratory |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nPlatt was born in Salford, England in 1942 and received his BSc at the University of Nottingham, UK.  He received his MA in 1965 from the University of Toronto, Canada for his thesis \u201c''Computer analysis of beam handling system for a linear accelerator''\u201d.  Later in the same year, Platt started work at the [[Bedford Institute of Oceanography]] in Dartmouth, Nova Scotia.<ref name=\"BIO1965\">{{cite book |last1=Bedford Institute of Oceanography |title=Fourth Annual Report |date=1965 |publisher=BIO 65-17 |location=Dartmouth, Nova Scotia |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/326613-65.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>  With the benefit of field and laboratory work conducted by his technical assistant Brian Irwin,<ref name=\"PlattIrwin1968\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T |last2=Irwin |first2=B |title=Primary productivity measurements in St. Margaret\u2019s Bay, 1967 |journal=Fisheries Research Board Technical Report Series |date=1968 |volume=77 |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/52277.pdf}}</ref> who joined the institute in 1966,<ref name=\"BIO1966\">{{cite book |last1=Bedford Institute of Oceanography |title=Fifth Annual Report |date=1966 |publisher=BIO 66-10 |location=Dartmouth, Nova Scotia |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/65672-66.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Platt embarked on studies that led to the fulfillment in 1970 of his PhD thesis (\u201c''Some effects of spatial and temporal heterogeneity on phytoplankton productivity''\u201d<ref name=\"BIO1970\">{{cite book |last1=Bedford Institute of Oceanography |title=Biennial Review 1969-1970 |date=1970 |publisher=BIO |location=Dartmouth, Nova Scotia |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/364599.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> at [[Dalhousie University]].\n\n==Research==\nPlatt's early research<ref name=\"BIO1968\">{{cite book |last1=Bedford Institute of Oceanography |title=Biennial Review 1967-1968 |date=1968 |location=Dartmouth, Nova Scotia |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/170235-67-68.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> was framed by the overarching goals originally envisioned by the founders of the Atlantic Oceanographic Group of the Fisheries Research Board of Canada at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography, namely: \u201c''to describe pathways and to measure amounts and rates of energy transfer in marine biological communities; and to study the structure and degree of organization of biological systems in the sea''\u201d.<ref name=\"BIO1965\" /><ref>Li WKW. 2014. Plankton ecology at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography, 1962-2012. In: Nettleship DN, Gordon DC, Lewis CFM, Latremouille MP [Eds.] 2014. Voyage of Discovery: Fifty Years of Marine Research at Canada's Bedford Institute of Oceanography, BIO-Oceans Association, Dartmouth, Nova Scotia, Canada. pp. 77-86. {{ISBN|978-0-9936443-0-6}}</ref>  One such early collaborative work<ref name=\"PlattRao1970\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Subba Rao |first2=D.V. |title=Energy flow and species diversity in a marine phytoplankton bloom. |journal=Nature |date=1970 |volume=227 |pages=1059\u20131060 |url=https://doi.org/10.1038/2271059a0 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> concerning energy flow and species diversity in marine phytoplankton blooms was motivated by the ideas of [[Ramon Margalef]], who evidently was nominated by Platt in a later year to receive one of three inaugural medals of the [[A.G. Huntsman Award for Excellence in the Marine Sciences]].\n\nIn the ensuing years, Platt, with collaborators, undertook a research program that progressed from investigations of the spatial inhomogeneity of plankton distribution in response to the power spectrum of turbulence,<ref name=\"PlattDenman1975\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Denman |first2=K.L. |title=Spectral analysis in ecology. |journal=Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics |date=1975 |volume=6 |pages=189\u2013210 |doi=10.1146/annurev.es.06.110175.001201}}</ref> through the physiological responses of the growth of cells in response to light and nutrients,<ref name=\"PlattJassby1976\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Jassby |first2=A.D. |title=The relationship between photosynthesis and light for natural assemblages of coastal marine phytoplankton. |journal=Journal of Phycology |date=1976 |volume=12 |pages=421\u2013430 |doi=10.1111/j.1529-8817.1976.tb02866.x}}</ref><ref name=\"PlattGallegosHarrison1980\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Gallegos |first2=C.L. |last3=Harrison |first3=W.G. |title=Photoinhibition of photosynthesis in natural assemblages of marine phytoplankton. |journal=Journal of Marine Research |date=1980 |volume=38 |issue=4 |pages=687\u2013701}}</ref> to dimensional analysis and the size structure of pelagic food chains,<ref name=\"PlattDenman1977\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Denman |first2=K.L. |title=Organisation in the pelagic ecosystem. |journal=Helgol\u00e4nder wissenschaftliche Meeresuntersuchungen |date=1977 |volume=30 |pages=575\u2013581 |doi=10.1007/BF02207862}}</ref><ref name=\"PlattSilvert1981\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Silvert |first2=W. |title=Ecology, physiology, allometry and dimensionality. |journal=Journal of Theoretical Biology |date=1981 |volume=93 |issue=4 |pages=855\u2013860 |doi=10.1016/0022-5193(81)90343-X}}</ref> and further to theoretical considerations of the limits of biological production in the ocean.<ref name=\"Platt-etal1989\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Harrison |first2=W.G. |last3=Lewis |first3=M.R. |last4=Li |first4=W.K.W. |last5=Sathyendranath |first5=S. |last6=Smith |first6=R.E. |last7=V\u00e9zina |first7=A.F. |title=Biological production of the oceans: the case for a consensus. |journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series |date=1989 |volume=52 |pages=77\u201388 |url=https://www.int-res.com/articles/meps/52/m052p077.pdf}}</ref><ref>Platt T, Lewis M, Geider R (1984)[https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4757-0387-0_3 Thermodynamics of the pelagic ecosystem: Elementary closure conditions for biological production in the open ocean.] In: Fasham M.J.R. (eds) Flows of Energy and Materials in Marine Ecosystems. NATO Conference Series, vol 13. pp. 49-84 Springer, Boston, MA</ref>\n\nBy the late 1980s, Platt's research program at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography<ref name=\"Clarke-etal2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Clarke |first1=A. |last2=Lazier |first2=J. |last3=Petrie |first3=B. |last4=Platt |first4=T. |last5=Smith |first5=P. |last6=Elliot |first6=J. |title=Ocean sciences \u2013 looking back at 40 years. |journal=Bedford Institute of Oceanography 2002 in Review: 40th Anniversary Edition |date=2003 |volume=Fisheries and Oceans Canada and Natural Resources Canada, Dartmouth, NS |pages=24\u201328 |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/353983.pdf}}</ref> had reached a stage where the solid foundations built from a close relationship between theoretical developments and observations at sea provided the ready capabilities to embrace the possibilities offered by satellite remote sensing of the ocean.  With his close collaborator Shubha Sathyendranath, Platt successfully implemented the analytical solutions and measurement-driven algorithms at regional and ocean basin scales to compute integrated primary production through the water column.<ref name=\"PlattSathyendranath1988\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Sathyendranath |first2=S. |title=Oceanic primary production: Estimation by remote sensing at local and regional scales. |journal=Science |date=1988 |volume=241 |issue=4873 |pages=1613\u20131620 |doi=10.1126/science.241.4873.1613}}</ref><ref name=\"Platt-etal1991\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Caverhill |first2=C. |last3=Sathyendranath |first3=S. |title=Basin\u2010scale estimates of oceanic primary production by remote sensing: The North Atlantic. |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research |date=1991 |volume=96 |issue=C8 |pages=15147\u201315159 |doi=10.1029/91JC01118}}</ref>  In 1995, the long-sought calculation of annual global production by marine phytoplankton was made possible for the first time,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Longhurst |first1=A. |last2=Sathyendranath |first2=S. |last3=Platt |first3=T. |last4=Caverhill |first4=C. |title=An estimate of global primary production in the ocean from satellite radiometer data. |journal=Journal of Plankton Research |date=1995 |volume=17 |pages=1245\u20131271 |doi=10.1093/plankt/17.6.1245}}</ref> after [[Alan Longhurst]] successfully partitioned the global ocean into a set of biogeochemical provinces within which the phytoplankton are likely subject to common physical forcing.<ref name=\"Longhurst1998\">{{cite book |last1=Longhurst |first1=A.R. |title=Ecological Geography of the Sea. |date=1998 |publisher=Academic Press |location=San Diego, CA |edition=First}}</ref>\n\nIn later years after the estimation of marine primary production at large geographical scale was made operational,<ref name=\"Platt-etal2008_RSE\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Sathyendranath |first2=S. |last3=Forget |first3=M.-H. |last4=White |first4=G.N. |last5=Caverhill |first5=C. |last6=Bouman |first6=H. |last7=Devred |first7=E. |last8=Son |first8=H.S. |title=Operational estimation of primary production at large geographical scales. |journal=Remote Sensing of the Environment |date=2008 |volume=112 |issue=8 |pages=3437\u20133448 |doi=10.1016/j.rse.2007.11.018}}</ref> Platt increasingly turned his attention to the use of remotely-sensed ocean colour as indicators of ecosystem performance<ref name=\"PlattSathyendranath2008\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Sathyendranath |first2=S. |title=Ecological indicators for the pelagic zone of the ocean from remote sensing. |journal=Remote Sensing of the Environment |date=2008 |volume=112 |pages=3426\u20133436 |doi=10.1016/j.rse.2007.10.016}}</ref> towards the management of fisheries<ref name=\"Platt-etal2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Fuentes-Yaco |first2=C. |last3=Frank |first3=K. |title=Spring algal bloom and larval fish survival. |journal=Nature |date=2003 |volume=423 |pages=398\u2013399 |doi=10.1038/423398b}}</ref> and stewardship of the ocean.<ref name=\"Racault-etal2019\">{{cite journal |last1=Racault |first1=M.-F. |last2=Abdulaziz |first2=A. |last3=George |first3=G. |last4=Menon |first4=N. |last5=Jasmin |first5=C. |last6=Punathil |first6=M. |last7=McConville |first7=K. |last8=Loveday |first8=B. |last9=Platt |first9=T. |last10=Sathyendranath |first10=S. |last11=Vijayan |first11=V. |title=Environmental reservoirs of Vibrio cholerae: Challenges and opportunities for ocean-color remote sensing. |journal=Remote Sensing |date=2019 |volume=11 |issue=23 |pages=2763 |doi=10.3390/rs11232763}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPlatt joined the Fisheries Research Board of Canada at the then three year old Bedford Institute of Oceanography in Dartmouth, Nova Scotia on June 22, 1965 as a research scientist in the public service.<ref name=\"BIO1965\" />  In 1972, he took over from [[Kenneth H. Mann]] as head of the Biological Oceanography Section.  He served as head until 2000, after which he remained in the section as senior research scientist.  In 2005, he transferred to the Coastal Ocean Science Section, still at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography, and remained there until his departure in 2008.  Platt was appointed Professorial Fellow at the Plymouth Marine Laboratory (UK) in 2008, and Jawaharlal Nehru Science Fellow at the Central Marine Fisheries Research Institute (India) in 2014.\n\nPlatt served the [[Association for the Sciences of Limnology and Oceanography]] (ASLO) for two separate terms as a member-at-large (1974-1977, 1986-1989), then as [https://www.aslo.org/about-aslo/board-of-directors/past-officers-and-board/ President (1990-1992)].\n  \nPlatt played an especially important role in the [https://ioccg.org/ International Ocean Colour Coordinating Group] (IOCCG), being one of the founding members of the group, and served as the [https://ioccg.org/about/past-committee-members/ first Chairman of the IOCCG] for a period of 10 years (from 1996-2006).\n\nPlatt also had a long association with the Partnership for Observation of the Global Ocean (POGO), first as a visiting Professor in 2005, and then as its Executive Director from 2008 to 2015.<ref name=\"PML2020\" />\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* 1981 APICS-Fraser Gold Medal<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simpson |first1=F.J. |last2=Atkinson |first2=J. |title=History of the Atlantic Provinces Council on the Sciences (APICS): The First Twenty-Five Years, 1962-1987. |journal=Atlantic Provinces Council on the Sciences |date=1993 |page=146 |url=https://scienceatlantic.ca/wp/site/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/apics-history-1962-1987.pdf}}</ref>\n* 1984 [https://www.rsmas.miami.edu/about-us/rosenstiel-award/past-recipients/index.html Rosenstiel Award]\n* 1988 [https://www.aslo.org/aslo-awards/g-evelyn-hutchinson-award/ G. Evelyn Hutchinson Award, American Society for Limnology and Oceanography]\n* 1990 [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada]]\n* 1992 [http://huntsmanaward.org/Laureates/1992_TrevorPlatt.htm A.G. Huntsman Award for Excellence in the Marine Sciences]\n* 1998 [https://royalsociety.org/people/trevor-platt-12101/ Fellow of the Royal Society]\n* 2006 [https://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/science/award-prix/recipients-recipiendaires-eng.html Timothy R. Parsons Medal]\n* 2007 [http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/science/publications/annualreport-rapportannuel/ar-ra0708/sect3-eng.htm#a1 DFO Prix d\u2019Excellence]\n* 2014 Jawaharlal Nehru Science Fellowship<ref name=\"Jayaraman2014\">{{cite journal |last1=Jayaraman |first1=K. |title=India kicks off fellowship for top visiting scientists. |journal=Nature News |date=2014 |url=https://www.nature.com/news/india-kicks-off-fellowship-for-top-visiting-scientists-1.14703}}</ref>\n*\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Platt, Trevor}}\n[[Category:British oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Canada]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British marine scientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Trevor Platt\n| honorific_suffix  = FRS, FRSC\n| image = Trevor_Platt.jpg\n| birth_date        = August 12, 1942\n| birth_place       = Salford, UK\n| death_date        = April 6, 2020\n| death_place       = Plymouth, UK\n| fields            = Oceanography\n| workplaces        = Bedford Institute of Oceanography, Plymouth Marine Laboratory\n| alma_mater        = Dalhousie University\n| known_for         = [https://doi.org/10.4319/lo.1976.21.4.0540 Mathematical formulation of the relationship between photosynthesis and light for phytoplankton] ([[PI curve|P-I curve]])\n| awards            = G. Evelyn Hutchinson Award, A.G. Huntsman Award\n| spouse = Shubha Sathyendranath\n}}\n\n'''Trevor Charles Platt''', FRS, FRSC (August 12, 1942 - April 6, 2020) was a British and Canadian biological oceanographer who was distinguished for his fundamental contributions to quantifying primary production by phytoplankton at various scales of space and time in the ocean.<ref name=\"PML2020\">{{cite web |last1=Anonymous |title=In memoriam: Professor Trevor Platt FRS |url=https://www.pml.ac.uk/News_and_media/News/In_memoriam_Professor_Trevor_Platt_FRS |website=Plymouth Marine Laboratory |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Early life and education==\nPlatt was born in Salford, England in 1942 and received his BSc at the University of Nottingham, UK.  He received his MA in 1965 from the University of Toronto, Canada for his thesis \u201c''Computer analysis of beam handling system for a linear accelerator''\u201d.  Later in the same year, Platt started work at the [[Bedford Institute of Oceanography]] in Dartmouth, Nova Scotia.<ref name=\"BIO1965\">{{cite book |last1=Bedford Institute of Oceanography |title=Fourth Annual Report |date=1965 |publisher=BIO 65-17 |location=Dartmouth, Nova Scotia |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/326613-65.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>  With the benefit of field and laboratory work conducted by his technical assistant Brian Irwin<ref name=\"PlattIrwin1968\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T |last2=Irwin |first2=B |title=Primary productivity measurements in St. Margaret\u2019s Bay, 1967 |journal=Fisheries Research Board Technical Report Series |date=1968 |volume=77 |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/52277.pdf}}</ref>, who joined the institute in 1966<ref name=\"BIO1966\">{{cite book |last1=Bedford Institute of Oceanography |title=Fifth Annual Report |date=1966 |publisher=BIO 66-10 |location=Dartmouth, Nova Scotia |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/65672-66.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>, Platt embarked on studies that led to the fulfillment in 1970 of his PhD thesis (\u201c''Some effects of spatial and temporal heterogeneity on phytoplankton productivity''\u201d<ref name=\"BIO1970\">{{cite book |last1=Bedford Institute of Oceanography |title=Biennial Review 1969-1970 |date=1970 |publisher=BIO |location=Dartmouth, Nova Scotia |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/364599.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> at [[Dalhousie University]].\n\n==Research==\nPlatt\u2019s early research<ref name=\"BIO1968\">{{cite book |last1=Bedford Institute of Oceanography |title=Biennial Review 1967-1968 |date=1968 |location=Dartmouth, Nova Scotia |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/170235-67-68.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> was framed by the overarching goals originally envisioned by the founders of the Atlantic Oceanographic Group of the Fisheries Research Board of Canada at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography, namely: \u201c''to describe pathways and to measure amounts and rates of energy transfer in marine biological communities; and to study the structure and degree of organization of biological systems in the sea''\u201d.<ref name=\"BIO1965\" /><ref>Li WKW. 2014. Plankton ecology at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography, 1962-2012. In: Nettleship DN, Gordon DC, Lewis CFM, Latremouille MP [Eds.] 2014. Voyage of Discovery: Fifty Years of Marine Research at Canada's Bedford Institute of Oceanography, BIO-Oceans Association, Dartmouth, Nova Scotia, Canada. pp. 77-86. {{ISBN|978-0-9936443-0-6}}</ref>  One such early collaborative work<ref name=\"PlattRao1970\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Subba Rao |first2=D.V. |title=Energy flow and species diversity in a marine phytoplankton bloom. |journal=Nature |date=1970 |volume=227 |pages=1059-1060 |url=https://doi.org/10.1038/2271059a0 |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> concerning energy flow and species diversity in marine phytoplankton blooms was motivated by the ideas of [[Ramon Margalef]], who evidently was nominated by Platt in a later year to receive one of three inaugural medals of the [[A.G. Huntsman Award for Excellence in the Marine Sciences]].\n\nIn the ensuing years, Platt, with collaborators, undertook a research program that progressed from investigations of the spatial inhomogeneity of plankton distribution in response to the power spectrum of turbulence<ref name=\"PlattDenman1975\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Denman |first2=K.L. |title=Spectral analysis in ecology. |journal=Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics |date=1975 |volume=6 |pages=189-210 |doi=10.1146/annurev.es.06.110175.001201}}</ref>, through the physiological responses of the growth of cells in response to light and nutrients<ref name=\"PlattJassby1976\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Jassby |first2=A.D. |title=The relationship between photosynthesis and light for natural assemblages of coastal marine phytoplankton. |journal=Journal of Phycology |date=1976 |volume=12 |pages=421-430 |doi=10.1111/j.1529-8817.1976.tb02866.x}}</ref><ref name=\"PlattGallegosHarrison1980\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Gallegos |first2=C.L. |last3=Harrison |first3=W.G. |title=Photoinhibition of photosynthesis in natural assemblages of marine phytoplankton. |journal=Journal of Marine Research |date=1980 |volume=38 |issue=4 |pages=687-701}}</ref>, to dimensional analysis and the size structure of pelagic food chains<ref name=\"PlattDenman1977\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Denman |first2=K.L. |title=Organisation in the pelagic ecosystem. |journal=Helgol\u00e4nder wissenschaftliche Meeresuntersuchungen |date=1977 |volume=30 |pages=575-581 |doi=10.1007/BF02207862}}</ref><ref name=\"PlattSilvert1981\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Silvert |first2=W. |title=Ecology, physiology, allometry and dimensionality. |journal=Journal of Theoretical Biology |date=1981 |volume=93 |issue=4 |pages=855-860 |doi=10.1016/0022-5193(81)90343-X}}</ref>, and further to theoretical considerations of the limits of biological production in the ocean<ref name=\"Platt-etal1989\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Harrison |first2=W.G. |last3=Lewis |first3=M.R. |last4=Li |first4=W.K.W. |last5=Sathyendranath |first5=S. |last6=Smith |first6=R.E. |last7=V\u00e9zina |first7=A.F. |title=Biological production of the oceans: the case for a consensus. |journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series |date=1989 |volume=52 |pages=77-88 |url=https://www.int-res.com/articles/meps/52/m052p077.pdf}}</ref>.<ref>Platt T, Lewis M, Geider R (1984)[https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4757-0387-0_3 Thermodynamics of the pelagic ecosystem: Elementary closure conditions for biological production in the open ocean.] In: Fasham M.J.R. (eds) Flows of Energy and Materials in Marine Ecosystems. NATO Conference Series, vol 13. pp. 49-84 Springer, Boston, MA</ref>\n\nBy the late 1980s, Platt\u2019s research program at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography<ref name=\"Clarke-etal2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Clarke |first1=A. |last2=Lazier |first2=J. |last3=Petrie |first3=B. |last4=Platt |first4=T. |last5=Smith |first5=P. |last6=Elliot |first6=J. |title=Ocean sciences \u2013 looking back at 40 years. |journal=Bedford Institute of Oceanography 2002 in Review: 40th Anniversary Edition |date=2003 |volume=Fisheries and Oceans Canada and Natural Resources Canada, Dartmouth, NS |pages=24-28 |url=https://waves-vagues.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/Library/353983.pdf}}</ref> had reached a stage where the solid foundations built from a close relationship between theoretical developments and observations at sea provided the ready capabilities to embrace the possibilities offered by satellite remote sensing of the ocean.  With his close collaborator Shubha Sathyendranath, Platt successfully implemented the analytical solutions and measurement-driven algorithms at regional and ocean basin scales to compute integrated primary production through the water column<ref name=\"PlattSathyendranath1988\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Sathyendranath |first2=S. |title=Oceanic primary production: Estimation by remote sensing at local and regional scales. |journal=Science |date=1988 |volume=241 |issue=4873 |pages=1613-1620 |doi=10.1126/science.241.4873.1613}}</ref><ref name=\"Platt-etal1991\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Caverhill |first2=C. |last3=Sathyendranath |first3=S. |title=Basin\u2010scale estimates of oceanic primary production by remote sensing: The North Atlantic. |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research |date=1991 |volume=96 |issue=C8 |pages=15147-15159 |doi=10.1029/91JC01118}}</ref>.  In 1995, the long-sought calculation of annual global production by marine phytoplankton was made possible for the first time<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Longhurst |first1=A. |last2=Sathyendranath |first2=S. |last3=Platt |first3=T. |last4=Caverhill |first4=C. |title=An estimate of global primary production in the ocean from satellite radiometer data. |journal=Journal of Plankton Research |date=1995 |volume=17 |pages=1245-1271 |doi=10.1093/plankt/17.6.1245}}</ref>, after [[Alan Longhurst]] successfully partitioned the global ocean into a set of biogeochemical provinces within which the phytoplankton are likely subject to common physical forcing<ref name=\"Longhurst1998\">{{cite book |last1=Longhurst |first1=A.R. |title=Ecological Geography of the Sea. |date=1998 |publisher=Academic Press |location=San Diego, CA |edition=First}}</ref>.\n\nIn later years after the estimation of marine primary production at large geographical scale was made operational<ref name=\"Platt-etal2008_RSE\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Sathyendranath |first2=S. |last3=Forget |first3=M.-H. |last4=White |first4=G.N. |last5=Caverhill |first5=C. |last6=Bouman |first6=H. |last7=Devred |first7=E. |last8=Son |first8=H.S. |title=Operational estimation of primary production at large geographical scales. |journal=Remote Sensing of the Environment |date=2008 |volume=112 |issue=8 |pages=3437-3448 |doi=10.1016/j.rse.2007.11.018}}</ref>, Platt increasingly turned his attention to the use of remotely-sensed ocean colour as indicators of ecosystem performance<ref name=\"PlattSathyendranath2008\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Sathyendranath |first2=S. |title=Ecological indicators for the pelagic zone of the ocean from remote sensing. |journal=Remote Sensing of the Environment |date=2008 |volume=112 |pages=3426-3436 |doi=10.1016/j.rse.2007.10.016}}</ref> towards the management of fisheries<ref name=\"Platt-etal2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Platt |first1=T. |last2=Fuentes-Yaco |first2=C. |last3=Frank |first3=K. |title=Spring algal bloom and larval fish survival. |journal=Nature |date=2003 |volume=423 |pages=398-399 |doi=10.1038/423398b}}</ref> and stewardship of the ocean.<ref name=\"Racault-etal2019\">{{cite journal |last1=Racault |first1=M.-F. |last2=Abdulaziz |first2=A. |last3=George |first3=G. |last4=Menon |first4=N. |last5=Jasmin |first5=C. |last6=Punathil |first6=M. |last7=McConville |first7=K. |last8=Loveday |first8=B. |last9=Platt |first9=T. |last10=Sathyendranath |first10=S. |last11=Vijayan |first11=V. |title=Environmental reservoirs of Vibrio cholerae: Challenges and opportunities for ocean-color remote sensing. |journal=Remote Sensing |date=2019 |volume=11 |issue=23 |pages=2763 |doi=10.3390/rs11232763}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPlatt joined the Fisheries Research Board of Canada at the then three year old Bedford Institute of Oceanography in Dartmouth, Nova Scotia on June 22, 1965 as a research scientist in the public service.<ref name=\"BIO1965\" />  In 1972, he took over from [[Kenneth H. Mann]] as head of the Biological Oceanography Section.  He served as head until 2000, after which he remained in the section as senior research scientist.  In 2005, he transferred to the Coastal Ocean Science Section, still at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography, and remained there until his departure in 2008.  Platt was appointed Professorial Fellow at the Plymouth Marine Laboratory (UK) in 2008, and Jawaharlal Nehru Science Fellow at the Central Marine Fisheries Research Institute (India) in 2014.\n\nPlatt served the [[Association for the Sciences of Limnology and Oceanography]] (ASLO) for two separate terms as a member-at-large (1974-1977, 1986-1989), then as [https://www.aslo.org/about-aslo/board-of-directors/past-officers-and-board/ President (1990-1992)].\n  \nPlatt played an especially important role in the [https://ioccg.org/ International Ocean Colour Coordinating Group] (IOCCG), being one of the founding members of the group, and served as the [https://ioccg.org/about/past-committee-members/ first Chairman of the IOCCG] for a period of 10 years (from 1996-2006).\n\nPlatt also had a long association with the Partnership for Observation of the Global Ocean (POGO), first as a visiting Professor in 2005, and then as its Executive Director from 2008 to 2015.<ref name=\"PML2020\" />\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* 1981 APICS-Fraser Gold Medal<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simpson |first1=F.J. |last2=Atkinson |first2=J. |title=History of the Atlantic Provinces Council on the Sciences (APICS): The First Twenty-Five Years, 1962-1987. |journal=Atlantic Provinces Council on the Sciences |date=1993 |page=146 |url=https://scienceatlantic.ca/wp/site/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/apics-history-1962-1987.pdf}}</ref>\n* 1984 [https://www.rsmas.miami.edu/about-us/rosenstiel-award/past-recipients/index.html Rosenstiel Award]\n* 1988 [https://www.aslo.org/aslo-awards/g-evelyn-hutchinson-award/ G. Evelyn Hutchinson Award, American Society for Limnology and Oceanography]\n* 1990 [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada]]\n* 1992 [http://huntsmanaward.org/Laureates/1992_TrevorPlatt.htm A.G. Huntsman Award for Excellence in the Marine Sciences]\n* 1998 [https://royalsociety.org/people/trevor-platt-12101/ Fellow of the Royal Society]\n* 2006 [https://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/science/award-prix/recipients-recipiendaires-eng.html Timothy R. Parsons Medal]\n* 2007 [http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/science/publications/annualreport-rapportannuel/ar-ra0708/sect3-eng.htm#a1 DFO Prix d\u2019Excellence]\n* 2014 Jawaharlal Nehru Science Fellowship<ref name=\"Jayaraman2014\">{{cite journal |last1=Jayaraman |first1=K. |title=India kicks off fellowship for top visiting scientists. |journal=Nature News |date=2014 |url=https://www.nature.com/news/india-kicks-off-fellowship-for-top-visiting-scientists-1.14703}}</ref>\n* \n==References==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Platt, Trevor}}\n[[Category:British oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Canadian oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Canada]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trevor_Platt"}
{"title_page": "Coates Kinney", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician and poet}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         =    Coates Kinney\n| image        =    Coates Kinney.jpg\n| image_size   =    \n| caption      =    \n| birth_date   =  {{ Birth date|1826|11|24 }}\n| death_date   =  {{ Death date and age|1904|1|25|1826|11|24 }}\n| birth_place  =    Penn Yan, New York\n| residence    =    East Second Street in Xenia, Ohio\n| occupation   =    Lawyer, politician, journalist, and poet\n}}\n\n[[File:East Second Street District, Xenia, 235.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Kinney's home on [[East Second Street Historic District (Xenia, Ohio)|East Second Street]] in Xenia]]\n\n'''Coates Kinney''' (November 24, 1826 \u2013 January 25, 1904) was an American lawyer, politician, journalist and poet who wrote ''Rain On The Roof''.A very nice poem.\n\n==Biography==\nCoates Kinney was born in 1826 near Penn Yan, New York. He was partly educated at Antioch College, Yellow Springs, Ohio, and studied law with Thomas Corwin. He was admitted to the bar in Cincinnati in 1856. He became a journalist, and worked on papers in Cincinnati, Ohio, Xenia, and [[Springfield, Illinois]].\n\nHe was a paymaster in the [[United States Army]] from June 1861 until November 1865, and was mustered out with the commission of brevet lieutenant-colonel of volunteers. He was a delegate to the convention that nominated [[Ulysses S. Grant]] for the presidency in 1868, and its Ohio secretary. He was senator from the 5th district in the Ohio legislature 1882-1883, and delivered a speech against \"The Official Rail Road Pass\".\n\nHe wrote poetry, and his verses were collected in ''Keeuka and Other Poems'' (Cincinnati, 1855) and ''Lyrics of the Ideal and the Real'' (1888). Of his verses, \"The Rain on the Roof\", which was set to music, was the most popular. He died in Ohio in 1904.\n\n==Works==\n*''Keeuka'' (1855)\n*''Lyrics of the Ideal and the Real'' (1888)\n*''Mists of Fire: A Trilogy and Some Eclogs'' (1899)\n*''Rain On The Roof''\n\n==Notes==\n{{no footnotes|date=July 2014 }}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite NIE|wstitle=Kinney, Coates|year=1905}}\n*{{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Kinney, Coates|year=1892}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Find a Grave|8631920|Coates Kinney}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=12689}}\n*[http://www.ohiohistoryhost.org/ohiomemory/archives/578 \"Poets of Ohio\"] (2012) from the [[Ohio Historical Society]] and the [[State Library of Ohio]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kinney, Coates}}\n[[Category:1826 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:Ohio lawyers]]\n[[Category:Ohio state senators]]\n[[Category:Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category:Antioch College alumni]]\n[[Category:People of Ohio in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Xenia, Ohio]]\n[[Category:19th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician and poet}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         =    Coates Kinney\n| image        =    Coates Kinney.jpg\n| image_size   =    \n| caption      =    \n| birth_date   =  {{ Birth date|1826|11|24 }}\n| death_date   =  {{ Death date and age|1904|1|25|1826|11|24 }}\n| birth_place  =    Penn Yan, New York\n| residence    =    East Second Street in Xenia, Ohio\n| occupation   =    Lawyer, politician, journalist, and poet\n}}\n\n[[File:East Second Street District, Xenia, 235.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Kinney's home on [[East Second Street Historic District (Xenia, Ohio)|East Second Street]] in Xenia]]\n\n'''Coates Kinney''' (November 24, 1826 \u2013 January 25, 1904) was an American lawyer, politician, journalist and poet who wrote ''Rain On The Roof''.\n\n\n==Biography==\nCoates Kinney was born in 1826 near Penn Yan, New York. He was partly educated at Antioch College, Yellow Springs, Ohio, and studied law with Thomas Corwin. He was admitted to the bar in Cincinnati in 1856. He became a journalist, and worked on papers in Cincinnati, Ohio, Xenia, and [[Springfield, Illinois]].\n\nHe was a paymaster in the [[United States Army]] from June 1861 until November 1865, and was mustered out with the commission of brevet lieutenant-colonel of volunteers. He was a delegate to the convention that nominated [[Ulysses S. Grant]] for the presidency in 1868, and its Ohio secretary. He was senator from the 5th district in the Ohio legislature 1882-1883, and delivered a speech against \"The Official Rail Road Pass\".\n\nHe wrote poetry, and his verses were collected in ''Keeuka and Other Poems'' (Cincinnati, 1855) and ''Lyrics of the Ideal and the Real'' (1888). Of his verses, \"The Rain on the Roof\", which was set to music, was the most popular. He died in Ohio in 1904.\n\n==Works==\n*''Keeuka'' (1855)\n*''Lyrics of the Ideal and the Real'' (1888)\n*''Mists of Fire: A Trilogy and Some Eclogs'' (1899)\n*''Rain On The Roof''\n\n==Notes==\n{{no footnotes|date=July 2014 }}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite NIE|wstitle=Kinney, Coates|year=1905}}\n*{{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Kinney, Coates|year=1892}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Find a Grave|8631920|Coates Kinney}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=12689}}\n*[http://www.ohiohistoryhost.org/ohiomemory/archives/578 \"Poets of Ohio\"] (2012) from the [[Ohio Historical Society]] and the [[State Library of Ohio]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kinney, Coates}}\n[[Category:1826 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:Ohio lawyers]]\n[[Category:Ohio state senators]]\n[[Category:Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category:Antioch College alumni]]\n[[Category:People of Ohio in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Xenia, Ohio]]\n[[Category:19th